Apply a moving average filter¶

In [9]:
window_size = 5
weights = (1. / window_size) * np.ones(window_size)
b = (1 / window_size) * np.ones(window_size);
a = np.array([1]);
zi = scipy.signal.lfilter_zi(b, a)

for _, group in train_data.groupby('engine_no'):
    indexes = group.index
    for column in train_data.columns[2:]:
        x = train_data[column][indexes]
        x_filt, _ = scipy.signal.lfilter(b, a, x, zi=zi*x.iloc[0])
        for i, index in enumerate(indexes):
            train_data.at[index, column] = x_filt[i]
            
features = train_data.columns[2:]
train_data.groupby('engine_no').get_group(1)[features].plot(subplots=True, sharey=False, width=350, height=200)

Dataset preparation¶

Normalization¶

In [11]:
eps = 1.e-6
train_mean = train_data.mean(axis=0)
train_std = train_data.std(axis=0)

for _, group in train_data.groupby('engine_no'):
    indexes = group.index
    for column in train_data.columns[2:]:
        x = train_data[column][indexes]
        x_norm = (x - train_mean[column]) / (train_std[column] + eps)

        for index in indexes:
            train_data.at[index, column] = x_norm[index]
 
for _, group in test_data.groupby('engine_no'):
    indexes = group.index
    for column in test_data.columns[2:-1]:
        x = test_data[column][indexes]
        x_norm = (x - train_mean[column]) / (train_std[column] + eps)

        for index in indexes:
            test_data.at[index, column] = x_norm[index]

Create dataset for MLP training¶

  • To do the model training the data from an engine is split into rolling windows so it has the dimensions (total number of rows, time steps per window, feature columns).

  • For an engine this would look like this for window size of 3:

      [1 2 3 4 5 6] -> [1 2 3], [2 3 4], [3 4 5], [4 5 6]

  • As training labels for each window the calculated RUL of the last value in the windowed sequence is picked.

      E.g. RUL=10:
  [1 2 3], 7
  [2 3 4], 6
  [3 4 5], 5
  [4 5 6], 4
In [12]:
train_rul = pd.DataFrame(train_data.groupby('engine_no')['time_in_cycles'].max()).reset_index()
train_rul.columns = ['engine_no', 'max']
train_data = train_data.merge(train_rul, on=['engine_no'], how='left')
train_data['RUL'] = train_data['max'] - train_data['time_in_cycles']
train_data.drop('max', axis=1, inplace=True)
In [25]:
def prepare_dataset(data, window_size, rul_threshold):
    samples = []
    labels = []

    dataset = data.set_index('time_in_cycles')
    data_per_engine = dataset.groupby('engine_no')

    for engine_no, engine_data in data_per_engine:
        # skip if the engines cycles are too few
        if len(engine_data) < window_size - 1:
            continue
            
        window_count = len(engine_data) - window_size

        for i in range(0, window_count):
            # take the last x cycles where x is the window size
            start = - window_size - i
            end = len(engine_data) - i
            inputs = engine_data.iloc[start:end]
            # use the RUL of the last cycle as label
            outputs = engine_data.iloc[end - 1, -1]

            inputs = inputs.drop(['engine_no', 'RUL'], axis=1)

            samples.append(inputs.values)
            labels.append(outputs)

    samples = np.array(samples)
    labels = np.array(labels)
    labels = labels.clip(max=rul_threshold)
    
    return samples, labels

window_size = 80
rul_threshold = 110
train_samples, train_labels = prepare_dataset(train_data, window_size, rul_threshold)
test_samples, test_labels = prepare_dataset(test_data, window_size, rul_threshold)

Train a prediction model¶

Create a MultiLayer Perceptron¶

In [16]:
from tensorflow import keras


model = keras.Sequential(
    [
        keras.layers.Input(shape=(window_size * len(features),)),
        keras.layers.Dense(32, activation='relu'),
        keras.layers.Dense(32, activation='relu'),
        keras.layers.Dense(32, activation='relu'),
        keras.layers.Dense(1)
    ])

model.summary()

Setup the training¶

In [17]:
optimizer = keras.optimizers.SGD(1.e-4)
metrics = []
metrics.append(keras.metrics.MeanAbsoluteError(name='mae'))
metrics.append(keras.metrics.RootMeanSquaredError(name='rmse'))
model.compile(loss='mse', optimizer=optimizer, metrics=metrics)
